nages to combine both immediacy and hindsight. It stands out for its descriptions of life and activities outside of the ghettos and concentration camps in wartime Poland and for its focus on Zionist youth resistance to the Holocaust. It also provides a somewhat rare female perspective on the Holocaust and offers insight into how much was known about the scale of the Nazi atrocities during the war. Following the book's initial publication in Hebrew in 1944, an unauthorized English-language edition was published in the United States in 1947. The present expanded text includes a scholarly introduction, notes, and a historical afterword, which help to explain and contextualize Kukielka's personal account.Published in association with the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust survivorszIsraelvBiography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zPolandzBędzinvBiography. 0aJewish ghettoszPolandzBędzinvBiography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xJewish resistancezPolandzBędzinvBiography. 4aGeneral Interest : Autobiography, Biography and Memoir. 4aHistory : History. 4aHistory : Holocaust Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aEzer, Paulina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHochberg, Severin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKovnat, Asya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849479140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438494791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438494791/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles